===Etymology 2===
{{ja-kanjitab|yomi=k|なんじ}}

{{IPAchar|/namuti/}} → {{IPAchar|*/nandi/}} → {{IPAchar|/nand͡ʑi/}}

From {{inh|ja|ojp|sort=なんじ|-}}.  Originally derived as a compound of {{compound|lang=ja|sort=なんじ|汝|tr1=na|t1=you|pos=ancient term|貴|tr2=muchi|pos2=honorific suffix}}.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref><ref name="DJR">{{R:Daijirin}}</ref><ref name="DJS">{{R:Daijisen}}</ref>

Originally used to refer {{l|en|honorifically}} to the {{l|en|second person}}.  From around the {{w|Nara period}}, the {{l|en|honorific}} sense lessened, and the term was used to refer to social {{l|en|equal}}s or occasionally social {{l|en|inferior}}s.  By the {{w|Muromachi period}}, this term was the most common {{l|en|second person}} {{l|en|pronoun}} for social {{l|en|inferior}}s.<ref name="KDJ">{{R:Kokugo Dai Jiten}}</ref>

